
All executable files in this directory are processed in shell expansion order.

  00_*: Reserved for 00_header.
  10_*: Native boot entries.
  20_*: Third party apps (e.g. memtest86+).

The number namespace in-between is configurable by system installer and/or
administrator.  For example, you can add an entry to boot another OS as
01_otheros, 11_otheros, etc, depending on the position you want it to occupy in
the menu; and then adjust the default setting via /etc/default/grub.


﻿First download the required files:
On the asus14 (BIOS) computer do the following:
Sudo apt install grub-pc
On the asus16 computer (UEFI) do the following:
Sudo apt install grub-efi-amd64
You should also get an i386-efi grub module if it is available
This may have to be done on different computers,depending on the configuration of the computer, such as a BIOS computer with MBR, a UEFI computer with GPT, etc.


Then use gdisk to create 4 partitions, a 2 M partition on the sector closest to the beginning of the disk - 2048 but prefer it to be 1.
Then an EFI partition of 500M
Then a boot partition of 500M
Then a data partition of the rest of the disk.
In addition to the GPT, also create an MBR in the expert menu of GPT and include the first 3 partitions.


Mkfs.vfat /dev/sda1
Mkfs.vfat /dev/sda2
Mkfs.vfat /dev/sda3
Mkfs.ext4 /dev/sda4




mount /dev/sda3 /mnt/boot
mkdir /mnt/boot/boot
mount /dev/sda2 /mnt/efi

Make sure the target sd card is on the asus-16 (UEFI) cpmputer when you type the following
grub-install --target=x86_64-efi --removable --no-nvram \
  --root-directory=/mnt/boot \
  --boot-directory=/mnt/boot/boot \
  --efi-directory=/mnt/efi

Make sure that the target SD card is on the asus14 (BIOS) computer when you do the following:
grub-install --target=i386-efi --removable --no-nvram \
  --root-directory=/mnt/boot \
  --boot-directory=/mnt/boot/boot \
  --efi-directory=/mnt/efi


grub-install --target=i386-pc \
  --root-directory=/mnt/boot \
  --boot-directory=/mnt/boot/boot \
  /dev/sdc


umount /mnt/efi
copy the /boot/grub/grub.cfg file to /mnt/boot/boot/grub
You need to change the grub.cfg file to have the right partition identifiers and also edit the /etc/fstab which will be in /mnt/root


mount /dev/sda4 /mnt/root


copy all the linux files to /mnt/root or dd the / partition for a working linux system.
edit the /etc/fstab file to have the correct partition ids.

If there is a problem with no sound, first use alsamixer <F6> to choose the sound card, then make sure to unmute all speakers and headphone with M and increase the volume with arrow keys.
Then use "systemctl restart --user wireplumber.service"

If when you boot it stops and you get intramfs> prompt then simply do fsck /dev/sd(abc) or whatever and reply y to all prompts. When it completes, the type exit.


That means GRUB loaded successfully but can't find its configuration file (grub.cfg).

At the GRUB command line, first let's find where your files are:

grub> ls
This will show you available drives like (hd0,gpt1), (hd0,gpt2) etc. Then look for your boot partition:

grub> ls (hd0,gpt1)/
grub> ls (hd0,gpt2)/
Keep trying each partition until you find the one with a boot or grub directory. Then:

grub> ls (hd0,gpt2)/boot/grub/
Once you find the grub.cfg file, tell GRUB where it is and boot:

grub> set root=(hd0,gpt2)
grub> configfile /boot/grub/grub.cfg

The most common cause of dropping to the GRUB command line even when grub.cfg exists is that the search command in grub.cfg is looking for a UUID that BIOS GRUB can't find. Paste the output and we can fix it.


The typical fix looks like changing from:

search --no-floppy --fs-uuid --set=root XXXX-XXXX
To:

search --no-floppy --file --set=root /boot/grub/grub.cfg
Or even simpler, just hardcode the root to whichever partition number you found worked at the GRUB command line:

set root=(hd0,gpt2)

The key change is replacing all the UUID-based search lines with:

search --no-floppy --file --set=root /boot/grub/grub.cfg
This finds the root partition by looking for a known file rather than a UUID, so it works regardless of which drive number the USB gets assigned on any machine — BIOS or UEFI.

Note that the linux and initrd lines still use root=UUID=... which is fine — that's the kernel parameter and works independently of GRUB's root detection.
There it is. The only changes from your original are that every occurrence of:

search --no-floppy --fs-uuid --set=root --hint-bios=... --hint-efi=... 77d2dbc4-...
and:

search --no-floppy --fs-uuid --set=root 77d2dbc4-...
has been replaced with:

search --no-floppy --file --set=root /boot/grub/grub.cfg
To apply it, on your USB (replace with your actual mount point):

bash
sudo parted /dev/sdX print free
If you see free space after the last partition, we can create the bios_grub partition there:

bash
sudo parted /dev/sdX unit MiB print free
This will show the exact start and end positions in MiB. Paste the output and I'll give you the exact numbers to use for mkpart.


bash
sudo parted /dev/sdX
```

Inside parted:
```
(parted) mkpart primary 59345MiB 59347MiB
(parted) set 2 bios_grub on        # replace 2 with the new partition number
(parted) print
(parted) quit
Then:

bash
sudo grub-install --target=i386-pc --boot-directory=/mnt/usb/boot /dev/sdX


